event.descr: The services scanning engine has asked discovery to pause due to a backlog of interfaces yet to be scanned.
event.logmsg: Capsd has asked Discovery to pause momentarily.

event.descr: Capsd is approving discovery to resume adding nodes to the Capsd queue.
event.logmsg: Capsd is ready for Discovery to resume scheduling nodes.

event.descr:
A services scan has been forced.

The administrator has forced a services scan on this node to update the list of supported services.
event.logmsg: A services scan has been forced on this node.

event.descr: A services scan has verified that this interface supports the SNMP protocol.
event.logmsg: A services scan has verified that this interface supports the SNMP protocol.

event.descr: Interface %interface% has been discovered and is being queued for a services scan.
event.logmsg: A new interface (%interface%) has been discovered and is being queued for a services scan.

event.descr:
The interface %interface% is being remanaged.

This interface will now participate in service polling.
event.logmsg: The interface %interface% is being remanaged.

event.descr:
The interface %interface% is being forcibly unmanaged.

This interface and all associated services will NOT be polled until the interface is remanaged.
event.logmsg: The interface %interface% is being forcibly unmanaged.

event.descr: A destination path in a notification has not been assigned any users.
event.logmsg: A destination path in a notification has not been assigned any users.

event.descr:
Notifications have been disabled.

The administrator has disabled notifications on OpenNMS. No pages or emails will be sent until notifications are reenabled.
event.logmsg: Notifications have been disabled.

event.descr:
Notifications have been enabled.

The administrator has enabled notifications on OpenNMS. Pages and/or emails will be sent based upon receipt of important events.
event.logmsg: Notifications have been enabled.

event.descr: The event configuration files have changed. The event services will now restart to detect the changes.
event.logmsg: The event configuration files have changed.

event.descr: The administrator has changed the poller configuration files. The pollers and related services will now restart to detect the changes.
event.logmsg: The poller configuration files have changed.

event.descr: SCM has been asked to restart.
event.logmsg: SCM has been asked to restart.

event.descr: This event is generated to RTC by any process that wishes to receive POSTs of RTC data.
event.logmsg: A subscription to RTC for the %parm[viewname]% for %parm[url]% has been generated.

event.descr: This event is generated to RTC by any subscribed process that wishes to discontinue receipt of POSTs of RTC data.
event.logmsg: Unsubscribe request received from %parm[url]%.

event.descr: The service %service% on interface %interface% is being remanaged.
event.logmsg: The service %service% on interface %interface% is being remanaged.

event.descr: The service %service% on interface %interface% is being forcibly unmanaged.
event.logmsg: The service %service% on interface %interface% is being forcibly unmanaged.

event.descr: The Scheduler has received an unrecognized service status from a scheduler.
event.logmsg: The Scheduler has received an unrecognized service status from a scheduler.

event.descr: %service% data collection on interface %interface% failed.
event.logmsg: %service% data collection on interface %interface% failed.

event.descr: %service% data collection on interface %interface% previously failed and has been restored.
event.logmsg: %service% data collection on interface %interface% prevously failed and has been restored.

event.descr:
Due to excessive downtime, the %service% service on interface %interface% has been scheduled for deletion.

When a service has been down for one week, it is determined to have been removed and will be deleted. If the service is later rediscovered, it will be re-added and associated with the appropriate interface.

If this is the only service associated with an interface, the interface will be scheduled for deletion as well, with the generation of the deleteInterface event.
event.logmsg: The %service% service on interface %interface% has been scheduled for deletion.

event.descr: Node #%nodeid% was determined to be a duplicate node and is being flagged for deletion.
event.logmsg: Node #%nodeid% was determined to be a duplicate node and is being flagged for deletion.

event.descr:
Interface %interface% deleted from node # %nodeid%

This event is generated following an extended outage for a service, in which that service is the only service associated with an interface. If the service is later rediscovered, a new interface will be added and the service will be associated with that new interface.
event.logmsg: Interface %interface% deleted from node #%nodeid%.

event.descr:
All services are down on interface %interface%

This event is generated when node outage processing determines that the critical service or all services on the interface are now down

New outage records have been created and service level availability calculations will be impacted until this outage is resolved.
event.logmsg: Interface %interface% is down.

event.descr: The hostname for this node changed.
event.logmsg: The hostname for this node changed.

event.descr:
SNMP Interface Index %parm[oldIfIndex]% has changed to %parm[newIfIndex]% on %interface%

The ifIndex, or unique numeric identifier of an SNMP device's interfaces, can be reordered by the SNMP agent. Usually this happens if interfaces are added or removed, or by a change in administrative or operational status.

This is typically not a reason for concern, but you should be aware that the active configuration on this SNMP device has changed, and the hardware configuration may have been impacted as well.
event.logmsg: SNMP Interface Index %parm[oldIfIndex]% has changed to %parm[newIfIndex]% on %interface%

event.descr:
Interface %interface% has been reparented under node %parm[newNodeID]% from node %parm[oldNodeID]%.

Usually this happens after a services scan discovers that a node with multiple interfaces is now running an SNMP agent and is therefore able to reparent the node's interfaces under a single node identifier.

This is typically not a reason for concern, but you should be aware that the node association of this interface has changed.
event.logmsg: %interface% has been reparented under node %parm[newNodeID]% from node %parm[oldNodeID]%.

event.descr:
The interface %interface% which was previously down is now up.

This event is generated when node outage processing determines that the critical service or all services on the interface are restored.

This event will cause any active outages associated with this interface to be cleared.
event.logmsg: Interface %interface% is up.

event.descr: A new node (%parm[nodelabel]%) was discovered by OpenNMS.
event.logmsg: A new node (%parm[nodelabel]%) was discovered by OpenNMS.

event.descr:
Node %nodeid% was deleted due to excessive downtime.

OpenNMS will delete any node that is down for seven (7) consecutive days. Nodes are considered "down" if there are no interfaces that have pollable services associated with them.

If a node becomes active again after it has been deleted, it will be rediscovered in the next, daily discovery cycle and will be re-added to OpenNMS's database as a new node. It will be disassociated with any historic outage information.
event.logmsg: Node %nodeid% was deleted due to excessive downtime.

event.descr:
All interfaces on node %parm[nodelabel]% are down.

This event is generated when node outage processing determines that all interfaces on the node are down.

New outage records have been created and service level availability calculations will be impacted until this outage is resolved.
event.logmsg: Node %parm[nodelabel]% is down.

event.descr: Interface %interface% has been associated with Node #%nodeid%.
event.logmsg: Interface %interface% has been associated with Node #%nodeid%.

event.descr:
A service scan has identified the %service% service on interface %interface%.

If this interface (%interface%) is within the list of ranges and specific addresses to be managed by OpenNMS, this service will be scheduled for regular availability checks.
event.logmsg: The %service% service has been discovered on interface %interface%.

event.descr: Node information has changed for node #%nodeid%.
event.logmsg: Node information has changed for %nodeid%.

event.descr: Node #%nodeid%'s label was changed from "%parm[oldNodeLabel]%" to "%parm[newNodeLabel]%".
event.logmsg: Node #%nodeid%'s label was changed from "%parm[oldNodeLabel]%" to "%parm[newNodeLabel]%".

event.descr:
A %service% outage was identified on interface %interface%.

A new Outage record has been created and service level availability calculations will be impacted until this outage is resolved.
event.logmsg: %service% outage identified on interface %interface%.

event.descr:
The %service% service on interface %interface% was previously down and has been restored.

This event is generated when a service which had previously failed polling attempts is again responding to polls by OpenNMS.

This event will cause any active outages associated with this service/interface combination to be cleared.
event.logmsg: The %service% outage on interface %interface% has been cleared. Service is restored.

event.descr:
Node %parm[nodelabel]% which was previously down is now up.

This event is generated when node outage processing determines that all interfaces on the node are up.

This event will cause any active outages associated with this node to be cleared.
event.logmsg: Node %parm[nodelabel]% is up.

event.descr: This event indicates that the interface selected for SNMP data collection for this node has changed. This is usually due to a network or address reconfiguration impacting this device.
event.logmsg: Primary SNMP interface for node %nodeid% has changed from %parm[oldPrimarySnmpAddress]% to %parm[newPrimarySnmpAddress]%.

event.descr: A change in configuration on this node has been detected and the SNMP data collection mechanism is being triggered to refresh its required profile of the remote node.
event.logmsg: SNMP information on %interface% is being refreshed for data collection purposes.

event.descr: The %service% service which was previously unresponsive is now responding normally on interface %interface%.
event.logmsg: %service% is responding normally on interface %interface%.

event.descr:
Service %service% was deleted from interface %interface%, associated with Node ID# %nodeid%.

When a service is deleted from an interface, it is due to extended downtime of that service of over seven (7) days.

If a previously deleted service becomes active again on an interface, it will be re-added to the OpenNMS database as a new occurrence of that service and will be disassociated with any historic outages.
event.logmsg: The %service% service was deleted from interface %interface%.

event.descr: The %service% service is up but was unresponsive during the last poll on interface %interface%.
event.logmsg: %service% is up but unresponsive on interface %interface%.

event.descr:
High threshold exceeded for %service% datasource %parm[ds]% on interface %interface%, parms: %parm[all]%

By default, OpenNMS watches some key parameters on devices in your network and will alert you with an event if certain conditions arise. For example, if the CPU utilization on your Cisco router maintains an inordinately high percentage of utilization for an extended period, an event will be generated. These thresholds are determined and configured based on vendor recommendations, tempered with real-world experience in working deployments.

This specific event indicates that a high threshold was exceeded.
event.logmsg: High threshold exceeded for %service% datasource %parm[ds]% on interface %interface%, parms: %parm[all]%

event.descr:
Low threshold exceeded for %service% datasource %parm[ds]% on interface %interface%, parms: %parm[all]%.

By default, OpenNMS watches some key parameters on devices in your network and will alert you with an event if certain conditions arise. For example, if the CPU utilization on your Cisco router maintains an inordinately high percentage of utilization for an extended period, an event will be generated. These thresholds are determined and configured based on working experience with real deployments, not vendor recommendation alone.

This specific event indicates that a low threshold was exceeded.
event.logmsg: Low threshold exceeded for %service% datasource %parm[ds]% on interface %interface%, parms: %parm[all]%

event.descr: %service% thresholding on interface %interface% failed.
event.logmsg: %service% thresholding on interface %interface% failed.

event.descr: %service% thresholding on interface %interface% previously failed and has been restored.
event.logmsg: %service% thresholding on interface %interface% prevously failed and has been restored.

event.descr: A vulnerabilities scan has been forced.
event.logmsg: A vulnerabilities scan has been forced on this interface.

event.descr: This trap means the X.25 PLE sent or received a restart packet. The restart that brings up the link should not send a x25Restart trap so the interface should send a linkUp trap. Sending this trap means the agent does not send a linkDown and linkUp trap.
event.logmsg: X.25 Restart: %parm[##]% args %parm[all]%

event.descr: If the PLE sends or receives a reset, the agent should send an x25Reset trap.
event.logmsg: X.25 Reset: %parm[##]% args %parm[all]%

event.descr: This dialCtlPeerCallInformation trap/inform is sent to the manager whenever a successful call clears, or a failed call attemp is determined to have ultimately failed. In the event that the call retry is active, then this is after all retry attempts have failed. However, only one such trap is sent between successful call attempts; subsequent call attemts result in no trap. ifOperStatus will return the operational status of the virtual interface associated with the peer to whom this call was made to.
event.logmsg: dialCtlPeerCallInfo trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% arguments: %parm[all]%

event.descr: This dialCtlPeerCallSetup trap/inform is sent to the manager whenever a call setup message is received or sent. ifOperStatus will return the operational status of the virtual interface associated with the peer to whom this call was made to.
event.logmsg: dialCtlPeerCallSetup trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% arguments: %parm[all]%

event.descr: This trap indicates that the indicated Virtual Circuit has changed state. It has either been created or invalidated, or has toggled between the active and inactive states.
event.logmsg: Frame Relay PVC state change: frCircuitIfIndex=%parm[#1]%; frCircuitDlci=%parm[#2]%; frCircuitState=%parm[#3]%

event.descr: An ospfIfStateChange trap signifies that there has been a change in the state of an OSPF virtual interface. This trap should be generated when the interface state regresses (e.g., goes from Point-to-Point to Down) or progresses to a terminal state (i.e., Point-to- Point).
event.logmsg: ospfVirtIfStateChang trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfNbrStateChange trap signifies that there has been a change in the state of a non-virtual OSPF neighbor. This trap should be generated when the neighbor state regresses (e.g., goes from Attempt or Full to 1-Way or Down) or progresses to a terminal state (e.g., 2-Way or Full). When an neighbor transitions from or to Full on non- broadcast multi- access and broadcast networks, the trap should be generated by the designated router. A designated router transitioning to Down will be noted by ospfIfStateChange.
event.logmsg: ospfNbrStateChange trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfIfStateChange trap signifies that there has been a change in the state of an OSPF virtual neighbor. This trap should be generated when the neighbor state regresses (e.g., goes from Attempt or Full to 1-Way or Down) or progresses to a terminal state (e.g., Full).
event.logmsg: ospfVirtNbrStateChange trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfIfConfigError trap signifies that a packet has been received on a non-virtual interface from a router whose configuration parameters conflict with this router's configuration parameters. Note that the event option Mismatch should cause a trap only if it prevents an adjacency from forming.
event.logmsg: ospfIfConfigError trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfConfigError trap signifies that a packet has been received on a virtual interface from a router whose configuration parameters conflict with this router's configuration parameters. Note that the event optionMismatch should cause a trap only if it prevents an adjacency from forming.
event.logmsg: ospfVirtIfConfigError trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfIfAuthFailure trap signifies that a packet has been received on a non-virtual interface from a router whose authentication key or authentication type conflicts with this router's authentication key or authentication type.
event.logmsg: ospfIfAuthFailure trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfVirtIfAuthFailure trap signifies that a packet has been received on a virtual interface from a router whose authentication key or authentication type conflicts with this router's authentication key or authentication type.
event.logmsg: ospfVirtIfAuthFailure trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfIfRxBadPacket trap signifies that an OSPF packet has been received on a non-virtual interface that cannot be parsed.
event.logmsg: ospfIfRxBadPacket trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfRxBadPacket trap signifies that an OSPF packet has been received on a virtual interface that cannot be parsed.
event.logmsg: ospfVirtIfRxBadPacket trap from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfTxRetransmit trap signifies than an OSPF packet has been retransmitted on a nonvirtual interface. All packets that may be retransmitted are associated with an LSDB entry. The LS type, LS ID, and Router ID are used to identify the LSDB entry.
event.logmsg: ospfTxRetransmit trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfTxRetransmit trap signifies than an OSPF packet has been retransmitted on a virtual interface. All packets that may be retransmitted are associated with an LSDB entry. The LS type, LS ID, and Router ID are used to identify the LSDB entry.
event.logmsg: ospfVirtIfTxRetransmit trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfOriginateLsa trap signifies that a new LSA has been originated by this router. This trap should not be invoked for simple refreshes of LSAs (which happesn every 30 minutes), but instead will only be invoked when an LSA is (re)originated due to a topology change. Additionally, this trap does not include LSAs that are being flushed because they have reached MaxAge.
event.logmsg: ospfOriginateLsa trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfMaxAgeLsa trap signifies that one of the LSA in the router's link-state database has aged to MaxAge.
event.logmsg: ospfMaxAgeLsa trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfLsdbOverflow trap signifies that the number of LSAs in the router's link-state database has exceeded ospfExtLsdbLimit.
event.logmsg: ospfLsdbOverflow trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfLsdbApproachingOverflow trap signifies that the number of LSAs in the router's linkstate database has exceeded ninety percent of ospfExtLsdbLimit.
event.logmsg: ospfLsdbApproachingOverflow trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: An ospfIfStateChange trap signifies that there has been a change in the state of a non-virtual OSPF interface. This trap should be generated when the interface state regresses (e.g., goes from Dr to Down) or progresses to a terminal state (i.e., Point-to-Point, DR Other, Dr, or Backup).
event.logmsg: ospfIfStateChange trap received from enterprise %id%

event.descr: The BGP Established event is generated when the BGP FSM enters the ESTABLISHED state.
The BGPBackwardTransition Event is generated when the BGP FSM moves from a higher numbered state to a lower numbered state.
This event is sent when an RMON device exceeds a preconfigured threshold.
This event is sent when an RMON device falls below a preconfigured threshold.
This event is sent when an RMON device matches a channel index.
event.logmsg: RMON Packet Match trap: Matched channel index #%parm[#1]% (%parm[#3]%); match count at %parm[#2]%

event.descr: The newRoot trap indicates that the sending agent has become the new root of the Spanning Tree; the trap is sent by a bridge soon after its election as the new root, e.g., upon expiration of the Topology Change Timer immediately subsequent to its election.
event.logmsg: Spanning tree root change from enterprise %id%

event.descr: A topologyChange trap is sent by a bridge when any of its configured ports transitions from the Learning state to the Forwarding state, or from the Forwarding state to the Blocking state. The trap is not sent if a newRoot trap is sent for the same transition.
event.logmsg: Spanning tree topology change from enterprise %id%

event.descr: The rptrHealth trap conveys information related to the operational status of the repeater. This trap is sent either when the value of rptrOperStatus changes, or upon completion of a non-disruptive test. The rptrHealth trap must contain the rptrOperStatus object. The agent may optionally include the rptrHealthText object in the varBind list. See the rptrOperStatus and rptrHealthText objects for descriptions of the information that is sent.
event.logmsg: Repeater health status change from enterprise %id% with args: rptrOperStatus=%parm[#1]%

event.descr: This trap is sent when a change occurs in the group structure of a repeater. This occurs only when a group is logically or physically removed from or added to a repeater. The varBind list contains the identifier of the group that was removed or added.
event.logmsg: rptrGroupChange trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% args: rptrGroupIndex=%parm[#1]%

event.descr: The rptrResetEvent trap conveys information related to the operational status of the repeater. This trap is sent on completion of a repeater reset action. A repeater reset action is defined as an a transition to the START state of Fig 9-2 in section 9 [IEEE 802.3 Std], when triggered by a management command (e.g., an SNMP Set on the rptrReset object). The rptrResetEvent trap is not sent when the agent restarts and sends an SNMP coldStart or warmStart trap. However, it is recommended that a repeater agent send the rptrOperStatus object as an optional object with its coldStart and warmStart trap PDUs.
event.logmsg: rptrResetEvent trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% args:rptrOperStatus=%parm[#1]%

event.descr: This trap indicates the failure of a BIND. The value of snaLuSessnLocalApplName indicates the local application name. The value of snaLuSessnPartnerName indicates the partner name. The value of snaLuSessnOperState indicates the current state after change. The value of snaLuSessnBindFailureReason indicates the failure reason. The Agent should not generate more than 1 trap of this type per minute to minimize the level of management traffic on the network.
event.logmsg: snaLuSessnBindFailure trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% arguments: %parm[all]%

event.descr: This trap indicates that the operational state (i.e., snaLuOperState value) of the LU has changed. The value of snaLuOperName indicates the name of the LU. The value of snaLuOperSnaName indicates the SNA name of LU. The value of snaLuOperState indicates the current state after change.
event.logmsg: snaLuStateChangeTrap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% arguments: %parm[all]%

event.descr: This trap indicates a Node activation failure. The value of snaNodeOperState indicates the current state after the activation attempt. The value of snaNodeOperActFailureReason indicates the failure reason.
event.logmsg: snaNodeActFailTrap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% arguments: %parm[all]%

event.descr: This trap indicates that the operational state (i.e., value of the snaNodeOperState object) of a Node has changed. The following variables are returned: snaNodeOperName -> current name of the Node, with the instance identifying the Node; and, snaNodeOperState -> current state after the change.
event.logmsg: snaNodeStateChange trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% arguments: %parm[all]%

event.descr: This trap indicates that the state of an SDLC port has transitioned to active or inactive.
This trap indicates that the state of an SDLC link station has transitioned to contacted or discontacted.

The dlswTrapCntlTConnPartnerReject trap is sent each time a transport connection is rejected by a partner DLSw during Capabilities Exchanges. The emission of this trap is controlled by dlswTrapCntlTConnPartnerReject.
event.logmsg: dlswTrapCntlTConnPartnerReject trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% args: dlswTConnOperTDomain=%parm[#1]%;dlswTConnOperRemoteTAddr=%parm[# 2]%

event.descr: The dlswTrapTConnProtViolation trap is sent each time a protocol violation is detected for a transport connection. The emission of this trap is controlled by dlswTrapCntlTConnProtViolation.
event.logmsg: dlswTrapTConnProtViolation trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% args: dlswTConnOperTDomain=%parm[#1]%;dlswTConnOperRemoteTAddr=%parm[# 2]%

event.descr: The dlswTrapTConnUp trap is sent each time a transport connection enters `connected' state. The emission of this trap is controlled by dlswTrapCntlTConn.
event.logmsg: dlswTrapTConnUp trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% args: dlswTConnOperTDomain=%parm[#1]%;dlswTConnOperRemoteTAddr=%parm[# 2]%

event.descr: The dlswTrapTConnDown trap is sent each time a transport connection enters `disconnected' state. The emission of this trap is controlled by dlswTrapCntlTConn.
The dlswTrapCircuitUp trap is sent each time a circuit enters `connected' state. The emission of this trap is controlled by dlswTrapCntlCircuit.
event.logmsg: dlswTrapCircuitUp trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% args: dlswCircuitS1Mac=%parm[#1]%;dlswCircuitS1Sap=%parm[#2]%;dlswCirc uitS2Mac=%parm[#3]%;dlswCircuitS2Sap=%parm[#4]%

event.descr: The dlswTrapCircuitDown trap is sent each time a circuit enters `disconnected' state. The emission of this trap is controlled by dlswTrapCntlCircuit.
event.logmsg: dlswTrapCircuitDown trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% args: dlswCircuitS1Mac=%parm[#1]%;dlswCircuitS1Sap=%parm[#2]%;dlswCirc uitS2Mac=%parm[#3]%;dlswCircuitS2Sap=%parm[#4]%

event.descr: The newFlow trap indicates that the originating system has installed a new flow in its classifier, or (when reservation authorization is in view) is prepared to install such a flow in the classifier and is requesting authorization. The objects included with the Notification may be used to read further information using the RSVP MIB. Authorization or non-authorization may be enacted by a write to the variable rsvpFlowStatus.
event.logmsg: newFlow trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% arguments: %parm[all]%

event.descr: The lostFlow trap indicates that the originating system has removed a flow in its classifier.
event.logmsg: lostFlow trap received from enterprise %id% with %parm[##]% arguments: %parm[all]%

event.event-label: Cisco Trap: Poor Quality of Voice (QoV)
event.descr:
A cvdcPoorQoVNotification is sent at the call disconnection time if the value of Calculated Planning Impairment Factor (ICPIF) exceeds the value of the ICPIF in the call associated peer.

  • Connection ID: %parm[.1.3.6.1.4.1.9.9.63.1.4.2.1.1]%
  • ICPIF Value: %parm[.1.3.6.1.4.1.9.9.63.1.4.2.1.18]%
  • Remote IP Address: %parm[.1.3.6.1.4.1.9.9.63.1.4.2.1.2]%
event.logmsg: Poor Quality of Voice (QoV) on VoIP call to %parm[.1.3.6.1.4.1.9.9.63.1.4.2.1.2]%.

event.descr: Indicates that the on-board temperature sensor has reported an overheat condition. System will shutdown until unit has sufficiently cooled such that operation may begin again. A cold start trap will be issued when the unit has come back on line.
event.logmsg: The agent %snmphost% has reported an overheat condition.

event.descr: Indicates one or more of the cooling fans inside the device has failed. A fanOK trap will be sent once the fan has attained normal operation.
event.logmsg: The agent %snmphost% has reported one or more cooling fans has failed.

event.descr: A fan has transitioned out of a failure state and is now operating correctly.
event.logmsg: The agent %snmphost% has reported that a previously failed fan is now operating.

event.descr: A user attempted to login to console or by telnet but was refused access due to incorrect username or password.
event.logmsg: The agent %snmphost% has reported a user attempted to login and was refused access.

event.descr: One or more sources of power to this agent has failed. Presumably a redundant power-supply has taken over.
event.logmsg: The agent %snmphost% has reported a failed power supply.

event.descr: One or more previously bad sources of power to this agent has come back to life without causing an agent restart.
event.logmsg: The agent %snmphost% has reported a previously failed power supply has been restored.

event.descr: Attached Redundant Power Supply device is indicating an alarm condition.
event.logmsg: The agent %snmphost% has reported an attached RPS device is indicating an alarm condition.

event.descr: Signifies that the value of one of the object identifiers defined in the extremeSmartTrapRulesTable has changed, and hence a new entry has been created in the extremeSmartTrapInstanceTable. Such a trap is sent at most once every thirty seconds if one or more entry was created in the last thirty seconds.
event.logmsg: The agent %snmphost% indicates a new entry has been created in the extremeSmartTrapInstanceTable.
